- **Anushilan Samiti**  ([Bengali](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bengali_language) : অনুশীলন সমিতি, [lit.](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Literal_translation)  'bodybuilding society') was an Indian organisation in the first quarter of the 20th century that supported revolutionary violence as the means for ending [British rule in India](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_rule_in_India) . The organisation arose [from a conglomeration](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Anushilan_Samiti)  of local youth groups and gyms (akhara) in [Bengal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bengal)  in 1902. It had two prominent, somewhat independent, arms in [East](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Bengal)  and [West Bengal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Bengal) , [Dhaka Anushilan Samiti](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dhaka_Anushilan_Samiti)  (centred in [Dhaka](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dhaka) , modern day [Bangladesh](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangladesh) ), and the [Jugantar](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jugantar)  group (centred at [Calcutta](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kolkata) ).
    - From its foundation to its dissolution during the 1930s, the Samiti challenged British rule in India by engaging in militant nationalism, including bombings, assassinations, and politically-motivated violence. The Samiti collaborated with other [revolutionary organisations in India](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revolutionary_movement_for_Indian_independence) and abroad. It was led by the nationalists [Aurobindo Ghosh](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aurobindo_Ghosh) and his brother [Barindra Ghosh](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barindra_Ghosh), and influenced by philosophies as diverse as [Hindu](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu) [Shakta philosophy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shakti), as set forth by Bengali authors [Bankim](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bankim_Chandra_Chattopadhyay) and [Vivekananda](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swami_Vivekananda), [Italian Nationalism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbonari), and the [Pan-Asianism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pan-Asianism) of [Kakuzo Okakura](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kakuzo_Okakura). The Samiti was involved in a number of noted incidents of revolutionary attacks against British interests and administration in India, including [early attempts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alipore_bomb_case) to assassinate [British Raj](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Raj) officials. These were followed by the [1912 attempt](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delhi-Lahore_Conspiracy) on the life of the Viceroy of India, and the [Seditious conspiracy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu-German_Conspiracy) during World War I, led by [Rash Behari Bose](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rash_Behari_Bose) and [Jatindranath Mukherjee](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jatindranath_Mukherjee) respectively.
    - The organisation moved away from its philosophy of violence in the 1920s due to the influence of the [Indian National Congress](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_National_Congress) and the [Gandhian non-violent movement](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_independence_movement). A section of the group, notably those associated with [Sachindranath Sanyal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sachindranath_Sanyal), remained active in the revolutionary movement, founding the [Hindustan Republican Association](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindustan_Republican_Association) in north India. A number of Congress leaders from Bengal, especially [Subhash Chandra Bose](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subhash_Chandra_Bose), were accused by the British Government of having links with the organisation during this time.
    - The Samiti's violent and radical philosophy revived in the 1930s, when it was involved in the [Kakori conspiracy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kakori_conspiracy), the [Chittagong armoury raid](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chittagong_armoury_raid), and other actions against the administration in British-occupied India.
    - Shortly after its inception, the organisation became the focus of an extensive police and intelligence operation which led to the founding of the [Special branch](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_Branch) of the [Calcutta Police](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calcutta_Police). Notable officers who led the police and intelligence operations against the  __ Samiti __  at various times included [Sir Robert Nathan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Robert_Nathan), [Sir Harold Stuart](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Harold_Stuart), [Sir Charles Stevenson-Moore](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Charles_Stevenson-Moore) and [Sir Charles Tegart](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Charles_Tegart). The threat posed by the activities of the  __ Samiti __  in Bengal during [World War I](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_I), along with the threat of a [Ghadarite uprising in Punjab](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghadar_mutiny), led to the passage of [Defence of India Act 1915](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defence_of_India_Act_1915). These measures enabled the arrest, internment, transportation and execution of a number of revolutionaries linked to the organisation, which crushed the East Bengal Branch. In the aftermath of the war, the [Rowlatt committee](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rowlatt_committee) recommended extending the Defence of India Act (as the [Rowlatt Act](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rowlatt_Act)) to thwart any possible revival of the  __ Samiti __  in Bengal and the Ghadarite movement in Punjab. After the war, the activities of the party led to the implementation of the [Bengal Criminal Law Amendment](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bengal_Criminal_Law_Amendment) in the early 1920s, which reinstated the powers of incarceration and detention from the Defence of India Act. However, the  __ Anushilan Samiti __  gradually disseminated into the Gandhian movement. Some of its members left for the Indian National Congress then led by [Subhas Chandra Bose](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subhas_Chandra_Bose), while others identified more closely with [Communism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communism). The  __ Jugantar __  branch formally dissolved in 1938. In independent India, the party in West Bengal evolved into the [Revolutionary Socialist Party](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revolutionary_Socialist_Party_(India)), while the Eastern Branch later evolved into the  __ __ [ __Shramik Krishak Samajbadi Dal__ ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shramik_Krishak_Samajbadi_Dal) __ __  (Workers and Peasants Socialist Party) in present-day [Bangladesh](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangladesh).
