- ^^**Atmiya Sabha**^^
    - **Atmiya Sabha**  was a philosophical discussion circle in India. The association was started by [Ram Mohan Roy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ram_Mohan_Roy)  in 1814 in [Kolkata](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kolkata)  (then Calcutta). They used to conduct debate and discussion sessions on philosophical topics, and also used to promote free and collective thinking and social reform. The foundation of Atmiya Sabha in 1814 is considered as the beginning of the modern age in Kolkata.[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmiya_Sabha#cite_note-EiSA-1) [[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmiya_Sabha#cite_note-Coward1987-2)  In 1823, the association became defunct.[[3]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmiya_Sabha#cite_note-Ksh%C4%ABras%C4%81gara1994-3)
    - The main activity of the  __ Sabha __   was conducting discussion and debate sessions on monotheistic [Hindu](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hinduism)  [Vedantism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vedanta)  and similar subjects. Weekly meetings used to be conducted in Ram Mohan Roy's garden-house in [Maniktala](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maniktala) .[[4]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmiya_Sabha#cite_note-Pruthi2004-4)  Most of these gatherings were informal and only a handful of Bengali intellects used to attend these meetings. It was not a formal organization, and there was not any membership registration procedure. However, the association intended to promote free and collective thinking. They also challenged and denounced orthodox religions.[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmiya_Sabha#cite_note-Coward1987-2)
