- ^^**Indian National Associatio**^^n
    - The **Indian Association**   was the first avowed nationalist organization founded in [British India](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_India)  by [Surendranath Banerjee](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surendranath_Banerjee)  and [Ananda Mohan Bose](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ananda_Mohan_Bose)  in 1876.[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_National_Association#cite_note-1)   The objectives of this Association were "promoting by every legitimate  means the political, intellectual and material advancement of the  people". The Association attracted educated Indians and **civics leaders**   from all parts of the country, and became an important forum for  India's aspirations for independence. It later merged with the [Indian National Congress](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_National_Congress) .
- 
- The Indian League
    - [Sisir Kumar Ghosh](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sisir_Kumar_Ghosh)  along with Sambhu Charan Mukherjee founded 'The India League' in Calcutta on 25 September 1875. The nationalist leaders like [Ananda Mohan Bose](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ananda_Mohan_Bose) , [Durga Mohan Das](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Durga_Mohan_Das) , [Nabagopal Mitra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nabagopal_Mitra) , [Surendranath Banerjee](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surendranath_Banerjee)   and others were associated with this organisation. The League  represented the middle class and worked to stimulate the sense of  nationalism among the people and to encourage political education. With a  broad vision of an all India outlook, the leaders kept the organisation  above narrow provincial and communal politics.
- 
- India League
    - **The India League**  originally was a Britain-based organisation whose aim was to campaign for the full independence and self-governance of India.[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India_League#cite_note-1)  It was formally established in 1928 by [Krishna Menon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V._K._Krishna_Menon)  and was the most influential and successful organisation in Britain during the 1930s and 1940s to fight against [British imperialism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Empire) .[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India_League#cite_note-:0-2)  In the early years, the India League was supported by stalwarts such as [Bertrand Russell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bertrand_Russell) , [Michael Foot](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Foot) , and [Jawaharlal Nehru](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jawaharlal_Nehru) ;[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India_League#cite_note-:0-2)  Russell and Foot both went on to [chair](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chairperson)  the League. Nehru, being very close friends with Menon, supported the League throughout.[[3]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India_League#cite_note-3)   The League was revived in 2020 and its new objectives include being a  think-tank which examines the views/needs of Indians in the UK.[[4]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India_League#cite_note-:4-4)  The name of this new entity is the 1928 Institute and it is affectionately called the League.[[4]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/India_League#cite_note-:4-4)
